Rating: 2
Made the recipe almost exactly as is, except I used a convection oven, and so reduced the cooking time and temperature (25*/25% rule). Also drained off the fat when turning the bird. I was disappointed with this recipe. It smelled amazing while cooking, but the meat turned out tough and dry, and the skin was not crispy (likely due to the flipping 2x). Also, the sauce was missing an element--I think a herb like thyme or rosemary would have saved it. I might try this again, but with duck parts, and not turning them so the skin is crispy. And I'll skip the sauce. The garlic-mustard rub followed with a thyme-pepper sprinkle idea is genius though, and I will try it on chicken.

Rating: 3
The sauce is delicious (not for kids with a full cup of port). I did add a dash of thyme to the sauce but it would have been just as terrific without it. Start on the sauce before you start the bird. It takes a while unless you cut a shortcut with veggie or chicken stock. Be careful if you have a convection oven, which was my case. Put the bird on the second lowest rack and keep an eye on it. You will likely need to reduce temperature after 20 minutes to 375, and after first 45 mins, when you turn the bird, you may wanna go down to 350 and roast the bird a little longer, to ensure it doesn't burn. Simply watch the colour. The other option is to tent the bird loosely with foil and continue at higher temperature and shorter times, but still watching carefully. Use a meat thermometer to ensure inner thigh of the bird has reached 170-180F. I will likely pour off fat from the roasting pan half way through the next time. A lot of fat separates from the bird. While my oven is self cleaning, it's still a nuisance to have to clean it every time after making this particular dish. Use a deeper roasting pan if you have one to reduce spatter. Make sure you do prick the skin (not meat) with a fork all over. This really helps release the fat during roasting. Using large sauce/saute pans helps reduce sauce very quickly. Use gravy separator to remove fat from the stock before you start reducing it. I used honey mustard in place of Dijon. The meat was rich tasting and tender. Your best bet is likely to serve this with a light salad or steamed veggies, but don't offer a side that will compete for taste. When buying the bird, if it touches very soft on the back and chest, it means it's fatty (you can literally see your finger imprints). Try to pick a slimmer, younger bird.

