Rating: 3
This is a fine recipe, but I can't believe it doesn't utilize the extremely flavorful pan drippings for the sauce. Here's what I did: After I removed the duck from the pan before serving, I poured off most of the duck fat (save it and roast some fingerling potatoes with it the next day - nothing's more delicious than duck fat!). I sauteed the garlic in the remaining drippings, added the port, reduced, and added the strained stock. Then finished and thickened it with softened butter, strained it again into the sauce boat. Incredible flavor and color! With this change, I'd give the recipe 4 forks easily.

Rating: 4
This is simply incredible! Instead of pricking the skin with a fork, I slash the skin and fat with a knife in a diamond pattern all over the bird being careful not to cut the flesh. This technique allows more fat to pour off the bird when it is flipped and hence you get a very nice crisp skin. I adjusted the time to 30, 25, 15 as someone else recommended, and it turned out perfect. Boyfriend said it was better than the duck he had in Paris at a 3 star restaurant. He didn't think that could be topped! I highly recommend.

